6&gt; Collision is non existant. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There are some incorrect/annoying &quot;features&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
True. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It is fun.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How so? Please tell me which aspects of the game you like. Again I ask the same question as I did to Flint. Besides being with cool people (I know the people you play with I like them all and just for that fact alone I might still be playing), and it is different from EQ. What grasps you and makes you feel a part of the world? At level 33 you may not have done a lot yet. You are just now getting into some of the higher content. Possibly some RVR so I can see why you would still like it if you have not done a lot of the RVR yet or the keep seiges. It is something new, which will lose luster after about 5 sessions. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It is most certainly incomplete<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Thank you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  So incomplete that it should have never been released in the first place.  Meanwhile that did not stop them from releasing it and collecting your money. Nice company. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There are certainly balance issues <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For the record I have no problem with balance issues. They will come about in every game, and every growing MMORPG will go through them. You can never tell how the classes will match up and what can be easily exploitable with each class until they are all on live servers. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Mythic seems to have done the 3 month crash course at the Verant School of Misinformation <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes they have. Although they have picked up a few lessons. &quot;How to stall a customer to get their money&quot;, &quot;How to shovel shit to the point of exhaustion&quot;, and my favorite &quot;To to make money on an MMORPG and do no work&quot;. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Hell, if I wrote a game, I would license the engines if I could. Why reinvent the wheel? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Here I go. <br>
<br>
No way in hell should an MMORPG game ever use a licensed engine, ever. <br>
<br>
For first person shooters lately the Quake 3 engine is being used and licensed from ID. In my opinion, and in this particular genre, it is fine. Why? Because these games all serve the same purpose. They are single player first person shooter games with multiplayer blow up sessions. <br>
<br>
Dark Age of Camelot should have never been licensed. The point itself means that they wanted something quick, effective, and to the point to make a quick buck. Which is exactly what we are seeing with the game. <br>
<br>
We pay $12.95 a month for this game to continue to succeed and hopefully grow and flourish. If they do not write the engine, they must wait on very key advances. Namely improvements which cannot be made now until they get another &quot;Upgrade&quot; to the license. This includes: <br>
<br>
1&gt; Water effects<br>
2&gt; Lava Effects<br>
3&gt; Any changes to the user interface<br>
4&gt; Any problems that might occur with the internal aspects of the game. <br>
<br>
Anything at all that happens internally that they want to change, they cannot do. <br>
<br>
I also take any word back on them having a smooth launch. This was NOT mythic's doing. It was the Netimmerse engine, and the people that made the guidelines for the servers and connections they should use. <br>
<br>
NI puts together an engine, tells mythic exactly how to set it up, it works bug free and stable. Mythic had nothing to do with it, they didn't code it. <br>
<br>
All Mythic did was get a couple level designers, a couple PR people and 5 CSR staff (Considering it takes about 5 days to get a reply, I am assuming this is how many they hired). License out an engine, and with a lot of PR made a lot of money. They paid roughly $300,000 for the engine, maybe about $200,000 in salaries to design the game, and some cash on the servers all totalling about 600,000 in start up. made it all back by giving the customers an option for a 6 month 60 dollar plan. Why not? People thought it was going to be great. <br>
<br>
Wrong. <br>
<br>
Now when the shit hits the fan? They stall and stall hoping they will get some answers out of the people that wrote the engine, and have to go through two channels of communcation before anyone at Mythic knows even how to patch the friggin game. <br>
<br>
Anything that isn't a simple spreadhseet fix will take months and months of stalling by Mark Jacobs, and anyone else at Mythic until someone can get a hold of their engine dev and figure out what to do. <br>
<br>
Case in point: The dex debuff bug. <br>
<br>
They announced it was a bug with the way the mobs reacted. Instead of changing the mobs, they knocked the spell value down to about 90% of its original value. For 2 weeks this goes on, until they can get a hold of someone that their engine company on how to adjust the mobs in regard to Dexterity. When they get technical support from the engine designers, they crrect the spell value back to the original value and the mob reacts differently now by being able to hit it more with a dex debuff. <br>
<br>
Strike you as odd?  <br>
<br>
How about the other millions of patchs they had destroying what they were balancing, only to fix it back to a state of its' original worth after they are able to figure out how to do it. <br>
<br>
If they had wrote the engine for the damn game they would know how. Instead all they did was hire about 5 defunct and burned out level designers from the old Starcraft days, (ever notice the dungeons are ALL THE SAME in every realm as far as layout? Just different names? Nice.) And now that they have to add content, they definitity have NO clue now how to do it. <br>
<br>
They have stalled major upgrades until the next engine because what they want to do simply doesn't exist yet, and they are waiting on this company to tell them what to do. <br>
<br>
This is a classic example of any dipshit out there that has enough money to get a couple people, license the engine and get enough for the bandwith and servers, can make any piece of shit and charge people for it, having no fucking clue which way is up. <br>
<br>
This proves once and for all that the only people that can make games are gamers themselves. This half-ass scam artist Mark Jacobs and his bullshit PR (Hell if you can't see right through the fact he hired the 2 most vocal people in our community, for the pure fact of no one ripping his game apart) than pays off any other reviewer out there (Yes promise them money or enough advertising profits from other companies and they will give shit reviews or great reviews - anyone can be bought) can make a game and reap the benefits without any purpose of coming through on any promises. <br>
<br>
Why? <br>
<br>
He saw MMORPG gamers are suckers. He sees people put up with incomplete games, bugs, dev problems,  in this genre and keep paying money because they hope the game will be improved. <br>
<br>
Now this asshole is laughing all the way to the bank with your money while he continues to give you bullshit monthly speeches which will NEVER come to fruition, while him and his bought off chronies continue to throw wild parties.  <br>
<br>
Definition of scammer is this guy. Point is he picked just the right people to scam. Serious game lovers that only wish to have a great MMORPG. When they see something that has the inner workings from being good, but is not, people will  keep paying and pray the game comes around. <br>
<br>
Which it never does. And by the time people realize it Mark Jacobs has already made about half a million off revenues and monthly subscriptions, closes up shop and throws in his old Steve Miller CD listening to &quot;Take the money and run&quot;.<br>
<br>
